FOOT & MOUTH DISEASE - ALGERIA (03): BOVINE, SPREAD, REQUEST FOR INFORMATION
****************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

[1]
Date: Wed 30 Jul 2014
Source: L'Expression (Algeria) [in French, mach. transl., summ., edited]
http://www.lexpressiondz.com/actualite/199279-un-foyer-identifie-et-75-bovins-decimes.html


Veterinary services called farmers in the region to take all measures to prevent the spread of FMD
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
After the appearance in May [2014] of foot-and-mouth disease (FMD) outbreaks in Tunisia and several suspected cases in Algeria [see comment], a new case was discovered in the town of Bir El Arch, in the wilaya [province] of Setif where 75 cattle were decimated by this epidemic.

According to the announcement of the Ministry of Agriculture and Rural Development published on Sunday [27 Jul 2014], the outbreak involves "a set of cattle breeders and horse dealers who keep exclusively fattening cattle. 75 head were destroyed and buried." According to the Director of Veterinary Services in the Ministry, Karim Boughanem, all measures to deal with this epidemic have been applied, including quarantine, animal movement restrictions, ring vaccination around the outbreak, disinfection and closure of livestock markets.

According to the explanations of veterinarians, the owners of the infected animals in Satif have concealed the disease.

It should be emphasized that FMD has not been present in Algeria since 1999, prevented by regular vaccination campaigns. The current outbreak was identified following the illegal introduction of cattle from Tunisia, infecting local cattle.

According to Dr Boughanem, the veterinary services have been on high alert to protect the region's cattle population. The affected area of about 20 sq km [about 7.7 sq miles] includes a high concentration of cattle, in particular fattening/feeder cattle.

The introduction of the disease means a serious situation with potentially grave economical implications. It can affect small ruminants as well. Dr Boughanem added: "Nevertheless, it is reassuring that we have a correct rate of immunization coverage, so even if the disease spreads, losses are expected to be limited." He reminded that 2 vaccination campaigns were conducted this year [2014], involving nearly 1.6 million heads out of the total national cattle population of around 1.8 million.

Another preventive vaccination campaign was launched in May [2014], just after the disease was reported, in April [2014], in Tunisia. Since then, some 750 000 cattle have been inoculated.

To stop the spread of this highly contagious disease and prevent mortality in animals, the ministry urged ranchers and farmers in the wilaya of Setif and neighboring wilayas, including Mila, Batna, Bordj Bou Arreridj, Constantine, Bouira, Jijel, Tizi Ouzou and Bejaia, to take several measures. This includes refraining from movement of animals except to the nearest slaughterhouse, not to attend cattle markets, avoiding the introduction of new animals into their farms and to systematically apply quicklime at the entrances to the premises, and to immediately report any suspected case.

[Byline: Kheireddine Boukhalfa]

